# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/act-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] Cockburn served as a member of the Privy Council, Treasurer Depute from 1699 until the accession of Anne, Lord Justice Clerk for a second term (1705–10), and a Lord of Session from 1705.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] He was Commissioner for Haddingtonshire at the Conventions of Estates in the years 1678, 1681, and 1689, and in Parliament of Scotland for the year 1690.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] He was nominated one of the Commissioners to treat on the Union of Parliaments, on 19 April 1689.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] Adam Cockburn was appointed Lord Justice Clerk in place of Sir George Campbell of Cessnock on 28 November 1692 and at about the same time was sworn a Privy Councillor.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] He was one of the Commissioners named to inquire into the Massacre of Glencoe on 28 May 1695, and became somewhat unpopular in some quarters because of the powers awarded to his position in order for him to reach conclusions in the matter.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] On 6 February 1699 he succeeded Lord Raith as Treasurer-depute of Scotland, which he retained until the accession of Queen Anne, when he was dismissed from all his offices.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] In 1695 he is one of the 30 or so wealthy merchants and officials setting up the "Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies" generally known simply as the Company of Scotland and being the instigator of the ruinous Darien Scheme.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] As he is also a signatory to the Act of Union 1707 he is one of the small group who were fully compensated for his losses in the Darien Scheme if agreeing to a Union with England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] As such (i.e. being named on each list) he was one of the Parcel of Rogues referred to by Robert Burns.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] Seen as an enlightened landlord, in 1698 he granted an 11-year lease to a Robert Wight, who was the first tenant farmer in Scotland to enclose his fields with a ditch and hedge, also planting trees with the hedgerow to act as a windbreak.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] Cockburn also enclosed his own estates at Ormiston.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] He obtained a commission appointing him a second time Lord Justice Clerk dated 8 January 1705 and was at the same time appointed to succeed Lord Whitelaw as a Lord Ordinary in the Court of Session.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] As Lord Justice Clerk, he received payment of £200 a year.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] In May 1714, he was one of the elders appointed by the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland to sit on a committee investigating disputes within the church.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] He left the office of Lord Justice Clerk again in 1710 but retained his place as a Lord Ordinary until his death, on 16 April 1735, in his 79th year.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] Adam Cockburn was the son of John Cockburn of Ormiston, and Janet Hepburn, daughter of Sir Adam Hepburn of Humbie.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] He was retoured heir to his brother John in the family's ancient estate of Ormiston, East Lothian, on 28 December 1671.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] Anne (died 1721), the twice-widowed daughter of Sir Patrick Houstoun, 1st Baronet, and mother of his son-in-law, Sir John Inglis of Cramond.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston] They had a daughter, Jean (1709 - 1792 Kelso, Scotland) who married William Walker.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne was born during the reign of her uncle King Charles II.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Her father was Charles's younger brother and heir presumptive, James, whose suspected Roman Catholicism was unpopular in England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] On Charles's instructions, Anne and her elder sister Mary were raised as Anglicans.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Mary married her Dutch Protestant cousin, William III of Orange, in 1677, and Anne married Prince George of Denmark, a Lutheran, in 1683.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] On Charles's death in 1685, James succeeded to the throne, but three years later he was deposed in the Glorious Revolution of 1688.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Although the sisters had been close, disagreements over Anne's finances, status, and choice of acquaintances arose shortly after Mary's accession and they became estranged.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] After Mary's death in 1694, William reigned alone until his own death in 1702, when Anne succeeded him.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] During her reign, Anne favoured moderate Tory politicians, who were more likely to share her Anglican religious views than their opponents, the Whigs.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Whigs grew more powerful during the course of the War of the Spanish Succession, until 1710 when Anne dismissed many of them from office.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Her close friendship with Sarah Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough, turned sour as the result of political differences.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Duchess took revenge with an unflattering description of the Queen in her memoirs, which was widely accepted by historians until Anne was reassessed in the late 20th century.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne was plagued by poor health throughout her life, and from her thirties she grew increasingly ill and obese.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Despite 17 pregnancies, she died without surviving issue and was the last monarch of the House of Stuart.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The loss of her young son, Prince William, precipitated a potential succession crisis.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Under the Act of Settlement 1701, which excluded all Catholics, Anne was succeeded by her second cousin George I of the House of Hanover.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne was born at 11:39 pm on 6 February 1665 at St James's Palace, London, the fourth child and second daughter of the Duke of York (later King James II and VII), and his first wife, Anne Hyde.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Her father was the younger brother of King Charles II, who ruled the three kingdoms of England, Scotland and Ireland, and her mother was the daughter of Lord Chancellor Edward Hyde, 1st Earl of Clarendon.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] At her Anglican baptism in the Chapel Royal at St James's, her elder sister, Mary, was one of her godparents, along with the Duchess of Monmouth and the Archbishop of Canterbury, Gilbert Sheldon.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne's parents had eight children, but Anne and Mary were the only ones to survive to adulthood.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] As a child, Anne had an eye condition, which manifested as excessive watering known as "defluxion".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] For medical treatment, she was sent to France, where she lived with her paternal grandmother, Henrietta Maria of France, at the Château de Colombes near Paris.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Following her grandmother's death in 1669, Anne lived with an aunt, Henrietta Anne, Duchess of Orléans.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] On the sudden death of her aunt in 1670, Anne returned to England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] As was traditional in the royal family, Anne and her sister were brought up separated from their father in their own establishment at Richmond in Surrey.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] On the instructions of Charles II, they were raised as Protestants, despite their father being a Catholic.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Placed in the care of Colonel Edward and Lady Frances Villiers, their education was focused on the teachings of the Anglican church.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Henry Compton, Bishop of London, was appointed as Anne's preceptor.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Her upbringing and education was typical for an aristocratic girl of her era, focusing on music, dancing, languages, drawing, and religion.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Around 1671, Anne first made the acquaintance of Sarah Jennings, who later became her close friend and one of her most influential advisors.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In about 1678, Jennings married John Churchill (the future Duke of Marlborough), who was the brother of Arabella Churchill, the Duke of York's mistress.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] He was to become Anne's most important general.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In 1673, James's conversion to Catholicism became public, and he married a Catholic princess, Mary of Modena, who was only six and a half years older than Anne.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Charles II had no legitimate children, and so James was next in the line of succession, followed by his two surviving daughters from his first marriage, Mary and Anne—as long as he had no son.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Over the next ten years, Mary of Modena had ten children, but all were either stillborn or died in infancy, leaving Mary and Anne second and third in the line of succession after their father.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] There is every indication that, throughout Anne's early life, she and her stepmother got on well together, and James was a conscientious and loving father.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In November 1677, Anne's sister, Mary, married their Dutch first cousin William III of Orange at St James's Palace, but Anne could not attend the wedding because she was confined to her room with smallpox.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] By the time she recovered, Mary had already left for her new life in the Netherlands.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Lady Frances Villiers contracted the disease and died.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne's aunt Lady Henrietta Hyde (the wife of Laurence Hyde) was appointed as her new governess.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] A year later, Anne and her stepmother visited Mary in Holland for two weeks.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Duke and Duchess of York retired to Brussels in March 1679 in the wake of anti-Catholic hysteria fed by the Popish Plot, and Anne visited them from the end of August.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In October, all three returned to Britain: Anne to England, and her father and stepmother to Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She joined them at Holyrood Palace in Edinburgh from July 1681 until May 1682.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] It was her last journey outside England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne's second cousin George of Hanover visited London for three months from December 1680, sparking rumours of a potential marriage between them.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Historian Edward Gregg dismissed the rumours as ungrounded, as her father was essentially exiled from court, and the Hanoverians planned to marry George to his first cousin Sophia Dorothea of Celle as part of a scheme to unite the Hanoverian inheritance.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Other rumours claimed she was courted by Lord Mulgrave, although he denied it.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Nevertheless, as a result of the gossip, he was temporarily dismissed from court.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] With George of Hanover out of contention as a suitor for Anne, King Charles looked elsewhere for an eligible prince who would be welcomed as a groom by his Protestant subjects but also acceptable to his Catholic ally Louis XIV of France.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Danes were Protestant allies of the French, and Louis XIV was keen on an Anglo-Danish alliance to contain the power of the Dutch.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] A marriage treaty between Anne and Prince George of Denmark, younger brother of King Christian V, was negotiated by Anne's uncle Laurence Hyde, who had been made Earl of Rochester, and the English Secretary of State for the Northern Department, Robert Spencer, 2nd Earl of Sunderland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne and George were second cousins once removed.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne's father consented to the marriage eagerly because it diminished the influence of his other son-in-law, William of Orange, who was naturally unhappy at the match.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Bishop Compton officiated at Anne and George's wedding on 28 July 1683 in the Chapel Royal at St James's Palace.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Although it was an arranged marriage, they were faithful and devoted partners.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] They were given a set of buildings, known as the Cockpit, in the Palace of Whitehall as their London residence, and Sarah Churchill was appointed one of Anne's ladies of the bedchamber.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Within months of the marriage, Anne was pregnant, but the baby was stillborn in May.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne recovered at the spa town of Tunbridge Wells, and over the next two years, gave birth to two daughters in quick succession: Mary and Anne Sophia.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] When Charles II died in 1685, Anne's father became King James II of England and VII of Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] To the consternation of the English people, James began to give Catholics military and administrative offices, in contravention of the Test Acts that were designed to prevent such appointments.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne shared the general concern, and continued to attend Anglican services.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] As her sister Mary lived in the Netherlands, Anne and her family were the only members of the royal family attending Protestant religious services in England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] When her father tried to get Anne to baptise her youngest daughter into the Catholic faith, Anne burst into tears.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] "[T]he doctrine of the Church of Rome is wicked and dangerous", she wrote to her sister, "their ceremonies—most of them—plain downright idolatry." Anne became estranged from her father and stepmother, as James moved to weaken the Church of England's power.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In early 1687, within a matter of days, Anne miscarried, her husband caught smallpox, and their two young daughters died of the same infection.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Lady Rachel Russell wrote that George and Anne had "taken [the deaths] very heavily ...
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Sometimes they wept, sometimes they mourned in words; then sat silent, hand in hand; he sick in bed, and she the carefullest nurse to him that can be imagined." Later that year, she suffered another stillbirth.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Public alarm at James's Catholicism increased when his wife, Mary of Modena, became pregnant for the first time since James's accession.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In letters to her sister Mary, Anne raised suspicions that the Queen was faking her pregnancy in an attempt to introduce a false heir.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She wrote, "they will stick at nothing, be it never so wicked, if it will promote their interest ... there may be foul play intended." Anne had another miscarriage in April 1688, and left London to recuperate in the spa town of Bath.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne's stepmother gave birth to a son, James Francis Edward Stuart, on 10 June 1688, and a Catholic succession became more likely.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne was still at Bath, so she did not witness the birth, which fed the belief that the child was spurious.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne may have left the capital deliberately to avoid being present, or because she was genuinely ill, but it is also possible that James desired the exclusion of all Protestants, including his daughter, from affairs of state.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] "I shall never now be satisfied", Anne wrote to her sister Mary, "whether the child be true or false.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] To dispel rumours of a supposititious child, James had 40 witnesses to the birth attend a Privy Council meeting, but Anne claimed she could not attend because she was pregnant (which she was not) and then declined to read the depositions because it was "not necessary".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] William of Orange invaded England on 5 November 1688 in the Glorious Revolution, which ultimately deposed King James.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Forbidden by James to pay Mary a projected visit in the spring of 1687, Anne corresponded with her and was aware of the plans to invade.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] On the advice of the Churchills, she refused to side with James after William landed and instead wrote to William on 18 November declaring her approval of his action.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Churchill abandoned the unpopular King James on the 24th.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] George followed suit that night, and in the evening of the following day James issued orders to place Sarah Churchill under house arrest at St James's Palace.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne and Sarah fled from Whitehall by a back staircase, putting themselves under the care of Bishop Compton.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] They spent one night in his house, and subsequently arrived at Nottingham on 1 December.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Two weeks later and escorted by a large company, Anne arrived at Oxford, where she met George in triumph.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] "God help me!", lamented James on discovering Anne's desertion on 26 November, "Even my children have forsaken me." On 19 December, Anne returned to London, where she was at once visited by William.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne showed no concern at the news of her father's flight, and instead merely asked for her usual game of cards.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She justified herself by saying that she "was used to play and never loved to do anything that looked like an affected constraint".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In January 1689, a Convention Parliament assembled in England and declared that James had effectively abdicated when he fled, and that the thrones of England and Ireland were therefore vacant.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Parliament or Estates of Scotland took similar action, and William and Mary were declared monarchs of all three realms.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Bill of Rights 1689 and Claim of Right Act 1689 settled the succession.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne and her descendants were to be in the line of succession after William and Mary, and they were to be followed by any descendants of William by a future marriage.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] On 24 July 1689, Anne gave birth to a son, Prince William, Duke of Gloucester, who, though ill, survived infancy.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] As William and Mary had no children, it looked as though Anne's son would inherit the Crown.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Soon after their accession, William and Mary rewarded John Churchill by granting him the Earldom of Marlborough and George was made Duke of Cumberland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne requested the use of Richmond Palace and a parliamentary allowance.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] William and Mary refused the first, and unsuccessfully opposed the latter, both of which caused tension between the two sisters.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne's resentment grew worse when William refused to allow George to serve in the military in an active capacity.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The new king and queen feared that Anne's financial independence would weaken their influence over her and allow her to organise a rival political faction.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] From around this time, at Anne's request she and Sarah Churchill, Lady Marlborough, began to call each other the pet names Mrs.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Freeman, respectively, to facilitate a relationship of greater equality between the two when they were alone.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In January 1692, suspecting that Marlborough was secretly conspiring with James's followers, the Jacobites, William and Mary dismissed him from all his offices.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In a public show of support for the Marlboroughs, Anne took Sarah to a social event at the palace, and refused her sister's request to dismiss Sarah from her household.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Lady Marlborough was subsequently removed from the royal household by the Lord Chamberlain, and Anne angrily left her royal lodgings and took up residence at Syon House, the home of the Duke of Somerset.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne was stripped of her guard of honour; courtiers were forbidden to visit her, and civic authorities were instructed to ignore her.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In April, Anne gave birth to a son who died within minutes.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Mary visited her, but instead of offering comfort took the opportunity to berate Anne once again for her friendship with Sarah.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Later that year, Anne moved to Berkeley House in Piccadilly, London, where she had a stillborn daughter in March 1693.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] When Mary died of smallpox in 1694, William continued to reign alone.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne became his heir apparent, since any children he might have by another wife were assigned to a lower place in the line of succession, and the two reconciled publicly.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] He restored her previous honours, allowed her to reside in St James's Palace, and gave her Mary's jewels, but excluded her from government and refrained from appointing her regent during his absences abroad.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Three months later, William restored Marlborough to his offices.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] With Anne's restoration at court, Berkeley House became a social centre for courtiers who had previously avoided contact with Anne and her husband.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] According to James, Anne wrote to him in 1696 requesting his permission to succeed William, and thereafter promising to restore the Crown to James's line at a convenient opportunity; he declined to give his consent.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She was probably trying to ensure her own succession by attempting to prevent a direct claim by James.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne's final pregnancy ended on 25 January 1700 with a stillbirth.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She had been pregnant at least 17 times over as many years, and had miscarriages or stillbirths at least 12 times.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Of her five liveborn children, four died before the age of two.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne experienced bouts of "gout" (pains in her limbs and eventually stomach and head) from at least 1698.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Based on her foetal losses and physical symptoms, she may have had systemic lupus erythematosus, or antiphospholipid syndrome.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Alternatively, pelvic inflammatory disease could explain why the onset of her symptoms roughly coincided with her penultimate pregnancy.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Other suggested causes of her failed pregnancies are listeriosis, diabetes, intrauterine growth retardation, and rhesus incompatibility.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Rhesus incompatibility, however, generally worsens with successive pregnancies, and so does not fit the pattern of Anne's pregnancies, as her only son to survive infancy, Prince William, Duke of Gloucester, was born after a series of stillbirths.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Experts also believe syphilis, porphyria and pelvic deformation to be unlikely as the symptoms are incompatible with her medical history.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne's gout rendered her lame for much of her later life.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Around the court, she was carried in a sedan chair, or used a wheelchair.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Around her estates, she used a one-horse chaise, which she drove herself "furiously like Jehu and a mighty hunter like Nimrod".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She gained weight as a result of her sedentary lifestyle; in Sarah's words, "she grew exceeding gross and corpulent.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] There was something of majesty in her look, but mixed with a gloominess of soul".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne's sole surviving child, the Duke of Gloucester, died at age 11 on 30 July 1700.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She and her husband were "overwhelmed with grief".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne ordered her household to observe a day of mourning every year on the anniversary of his death.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] With William childless and Gloucester dead, Anne was the only person remaining in the line of succession established by the Bill of Rights 1689.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Sophia was the granddaughter of James VI and I through his daughter Elizabeth, who was the sister of Anne's grandfather Charles I.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Over 50 Catholics with stronger claims were excluded from the line of succession.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] His widow, the former queen, wrote to Anne to inform her that her father forgave her and to remind her of her promise to seek the restoration of his line, but Anne had already acquiesced to the line of succession created by the Act of Settlement.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne became queen upon the death of King William III on 8 March 1702, and was immediately popular.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Soon after her accession, Anne appointed her husband Lord High Admiral, giving him nominal control of the Royal Navy.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne gave control of the army to Lord Marlborough, whom she appointed Captain-General.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Marlborough also received numerous honours from the Queen; he was created a Knight of the Garter and was elevated to the rank of duke.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Duchess of Marlborough was appointed Groom of the Stool, Mistress of the Robes, and Keeper of the Privy Purse.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne was crowned on St George's Day, 23 April 1702.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Affected by gout, she was carried to Westminster Abbey in an open sedan chair, with a low back to permit her train to flow out behind her.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] On 4 May, England became embroiled in the War of the Spanish Succession, in which England, Austria, and the Dutch Republic fought against France and Bourbon Spain.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Charles II of Spain had died childless in 1700, and the succession was disputed by two claimants: the Habsburg Archduke Charles of Austria and the Bourbon Philip, Duke of Anjou.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She took a lively interest in affairs of state, and was a patron of theatre, poetry and music.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She subsidised George Frideric Handel with £200 a year.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She sponsored high-quality medals as rewards for political or military achievements.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] They were produced at the Mint by Isaac Newton and John Croker.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She knighted Newton when she visited Cambridge in 1705.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] While Ireland was subordinate to the English Crown and Wales formed part of the kingdom of England, Scotland remained an independent sovereign state with its own parliament and laws.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Act of Settlement 1701, passed by the English Parliament, applied in the kingdoms of England and Ireland but not Scotland, where a strong minority wished to preserve the Stuart dynasty and its right of inheritance to the throne.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne had declared it "very necessary" to conclude a union of England and Scotland in her first speech to the English Parliament, and a joint Anglo-Scots commission met at her former residence, the Cockpit, to discuss terms in October 1702.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The negotiations broke up in early February 1703 having failed to reach an agreement.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Estates of Scotland responded to the Act of Settlement by passing the Act of Security, which gave the Estates the power, if the Queen had no further children, to choose the next Scottish monarch from among the Protestant descendants of the royal line of Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The individual chosen by the Estates could not be the same person who came to the English throne, unless England granted full freedom of trade to Scottish merchants.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] At first, Anne withheld royal assent to the act, but she granted it the following year when the Estates threatened to withhold supply, endangering Scottish support for England's wars.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In its turn, the English Parliament responded with the Alien Act 1705, which threatened to impose economic sanctions and declare Scottish subjects aliens in England, unless Scotland either repealed the Act of Security or moved to unite with England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Estates chose the latter option; the English Parliament agreed to repeal the Alien Act, and new commissioners were appointed by Queen Anne in early 1706 to negotiate the terms of a union.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The articles of union approved by the commissioners were presented to Anne on 23 July 1706 and ratified by the Scottish and English Parliaments on 16 January and 6 March 1707, respectively.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Under the Acts of Union, England and Scotland were united into a single kingdom called Great Britain, with one parliament, on 1 May 1707.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] A consistent and ardent supporter of union despite opposition on both sides of the border, Anne attended a thanksgiving service in St Paul's Cathedral.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Scot Sir John Clerk, 1st Baronet, who also attended, wrote, "nobody on this occasion appeared more sincerely devout and thankful than the Queen herself".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne's reign was marked by the further development of a two-party system.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In general, the Tories were supportive of the Anglican church and favoured the landed interest of the country gentry, while the Whigs were aligned with commercial interests and Protestant Dissenters.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] As a committed Anglican, Anne was inclined to favour the Tories.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Her first ministry was predominantly Tory, and contained such High Tories as Daniel Finch, 2nd Earl of Nottingham, and her uncle Laurence Hyde, 1st Earl of Rochester.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] It was headed by Lord Treasurer Lord Godolphin and Anne's favourite the Duke of Marlborough, who were considered moderate Tories, along with the Speaker of the House of Commons, Robert Harley.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne supported the Occasional Conformity Bill of 1702, which was promoted by the Tories and opposed by the Whigs.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The bill aimed to disqualify Protestant Dissenters from public office by closing a loophole in the Test Acts, legislation that restricted public office to Anglican conformists.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The existing law permitted nonconformists to take office if they took Anglican communion once a year.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne's husband was placed in an unfortunate position when Anne forced him to vote for the bill, even though, being a Lutheran, he was an occasional conformist himself.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Whigs successfully blocked the bill for the duration of the parliamentary session.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne reinstituted the traditional religious practice of touching for the king's evil that had been eschewed by William as papist superstition.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] After the Great Storm of 1703, Anne declared a general fast to implore God "to pardon the crying sins of this nation which had drawn down this sad judgement".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Occasional Conformity Bill was revived in the wake of the storm, but Anne withheld support, fearing its reintroduction was a ruse to cause a political quarrel.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] A third attempt to introduce the bill as an amendment to a money bill in November 1704 was also thwarted.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Whigs vigorously supported the War of the Spanish Succession and became even more influential after the Duke of Marlborough won a great victory at the Battle of Blenheim in 1704.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Many of the High Tories, who opposed British involvement in the land war against France, were removed from office.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Godolphin, Marlborough, and Harley, who had replaced Nottingham as Secretary of State for the Northern Department, formed a ruling "triumvirate".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] They were forced to rely more and more on support from the Whigs, and particularly from the Whig Junto—Lords Somers, Halifax, Orford, Wharton and Sunderland—whom Anne disliked.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Sarah, the Duchess of Marlborough, incessantly badgered the Queen to appoint more Whigs and reduce the power of the Tories, whom she considered little better than Jacobites, and the Queen became increasingly discontented with her.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In 1706, Godolphin and the Marlboroughs forced Anne to accept Lord Sunderland, a Junto Whig and the Marlboroughs' son-in-law, as Harley's colleague as Secretary of State for the Southern Department.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Queen turned for private advice to Harley, who was uncomfortable with Marlborough and Godolphin's turn towards the Whigs.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She also turned to Abigail Hill, a woman of the bedchamber whose influence grew as Anne's relationship with Sarah deteriorated.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Abigail was related to both Harley and the Duchess, but was politically closer to Harley, and acted as an intermediary between him and the Queen.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The division within the ministry came to a head on 8 February 1708, when Godolphin and the Marlboroughs insisted that the Queen had to either dismiss Harley or do without their services.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] When the Queen seemed to hesitate, Marlborough and Godolphin refused to attend a cabinet meeting.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Harley attempted to lead business without his former colleagues, and several of those present including Charles Seymour, Duke of Somerset refused to participate until they returned.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Her hand forced, the Queen dismissed Harley.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The following month, Anne's Catholic half-brother, James Francis Edward Stuart, attempted to land in Scotland with French assistance in an attempt to establish himself as king.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne withheld royal assent from the Scottish Militia Bill 1708 in case the militia raised in Scotland was disloyal and sided with the Jacobites.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She was the last British sovereign to veto a parliamentary bill, although her action was barely commented upon at the time.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The invasion fleet never landed and was chased away by British ships commanded by Sir George Byng.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] As a result of the Jacobite invasion scare, support for the Tories fell and the Whigs were able to secure a majority in the 1708 British general election.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Duchess of Marlborough was angered when Abigail moved into rooms at Kensington Palace that Sarah considered her own, though she rarely if ever used them.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In July 1708, she came to court with a bawdy poem written by a Whig propagandist, probably Arthur Maynwaring, that implied a lesbian relationship between Anne and Abigail.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Duchess wrote to Anne telling her she had damaged her reputation by conceiving "a great passion for such a woman ... strange and unaccountable".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Sarah thought Abigail had risen above her station, writing "I never thought her education was such as to make her fit company for a great queen.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Many people have liked the humour of their chambermaids and have been very kind to them, but 'tis very uncommon to hold a private correspondence with them and put them upon the foot of a friend." While some modern commentators have concluded Anne was a lesbian, most have rejected this analysis.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In the opinion of Anne's biographers, she considered Abigail nothing more than a trusted servant and was a woman of strong traditional beliefs who was devoted to her husband.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] At a thanksgiving service for a victory at the Battle of Oudenarde, Anne did not wear the jewels that Sarah had selected for her.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] At the door of St Paul's Cathedral, they had an argument that culminated in Sarah offending the Queen by telling her to be quiet.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne was devastated by Prince George's death in October 1708, and it proved a turning point in her relationship with the Duchess of Marlborough.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Duchess arrived at Kensington Palace shortly before George died, and after his death insisted that Anne leave Kensington for St James's Palace against her wishes.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne resented the Duchess's intrusive actions, which included removing a portrait of George from the Queen's bedchamber and then refusing to return it in the belief that it was natural "to avoid seeing of papers or anything that belonged to one that one loved when they were just dead".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Whigs used George's death to their own advantage.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The leadership of the Admiralty was unpopular among the Whig leaders, who had blamed Prince George and his deputy George Churchill (who was Marlborough's brother) for mismanagement of the navy.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] With Whigs now dominant in Parliament, and Anne distraught at the loss of her husband, they forced her to accept the Junto leaders Lords Somers and Wharton into the cabinet.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne, however, insisted on carrying out the duties of Lord High Admiral herself, without appointing a member of the government to take George's place.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Undeterred, the Junto demanded the appointment of the Earl of Orford, another member of the Junto and one of the prince's leading critics, as First Lord of the Admiralty.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne appointed the moderate Earl of Pembroke, on 29 November 1708.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Pressure mounted on Pembroke, Godolphin and the Queen from the dissatisfied Junto Whigs, and Pembroke resigned after less than a year in office.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Another month of arguments followed before the Queen finally consented to put Orford in control of the Admiralty as First Lord in November 1709.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Sarah continued to berate Anne for her friendship with Abigail and, in October 1709, Anne wrote to the Duke of Marlborough asking that his wife "leave off teasing & tormenting me & behave herself with the decency she ought both to her friend and Queen".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] On Maundy Thursday 6 April 1710, Anne and Sarah saw each other for the last time.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] According to Sarah, the Queen was taciturn and formal, repeating the same phrases—"Whatever you have to say you may put in writing" and "You said you desired no answer, and I shall give you none"—over and over.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] As the expensive War of the Spanish Succession grew unpopular, so did the Whig administration.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The impeachment of Henry Sacheverell, a high church Tory Anglican who had preached anti-Whig sermons, led to further public discontent.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne thought Sacheverell ought to be punished for questioning the Glorious Revolution, but that his punishment should only be a mild one to prevent further public commotion.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In London, riots broke out in support of Sacheverell, but the only troops available to quell the disturbances were Anne's guards, and Secretary of State Sunderland was reluctant to use them and leave the Queen less protected.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne declared God would be her guard and ordered Sunderland to redeploy her troops.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In line with Anne's views, Sacheverell was convicted, but his sentence—suspension of preaching for three years—was so light as to render the trial a mockery.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Queen, increasingly disdainful of the Marlboroughs and her ministry, finally took the opportunity to dismiss Sunderland in June 1710.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Junto Whigs were removed from office, although Marlborough, for the moment, remained as commander of the army.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In their place, she appointed a new ministry headed by Harley, which began to seek peace with France.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Unlike the Whigs, Harley and his ministry were ready to compromise by giving Spain to the Bourbon claimant, Philip of Anjou, in return for commercial concessions.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In the parliamentary elections that soon followed his appointment, Harley, aided by government patronage, secured a large Tory majority.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In January 1711, Anne forced Sarah to resign her court offices, and Abigail took over as Keeper of the Privy Purse.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Harley was stabbed by a disgruntled French refugee, the Marquis de Guiscard, in March, and Anne wept at the thought he would die.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Godolphin's death from natural causes in September 1712 reduced Anne to tears; she blamed their estrangement on the Marlboroughs.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The elder brother of Archduke Charles, Emperor Joseph I, died in April 1711 and Charles succeeded him in Austria, Hungary and the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] To also give him the Spanish throne was no longer in Britain's interests, but the proposed Peace of Utrecht submitted to Parliament for ratification did not go as far as the Whigs wanted to curb Bourbon ambitions.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In the House of Commons, the Tory majority was unassailable, but the same was not true in the House of Lords.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Whigs secured the support of the Earl of Nottingham against the treaty by promising to support his Occasional Conformity bill.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Seeing a need for decisive action to erase the anti-peace majority in the House of Lords, and seeing no alternative, Anne reluctantly created twelve new peers, even though such a mass creation of peers was unprecedented.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Abigail's husband, Samuel Masham, was made a baron, although Anne protested to Harley that she "never had any design to make a great lady of [Abigail], and should lose a useful servant".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] On the same day, Marlborough was dismissed as commander of the army.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The peace treaty was ratified and Britain's military involvement in the War of the Spanish Succession ended.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] By signing the Treaty of Utrecht, Louis XIV of France recognised the Hanoverian succession in Britain.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Nevertheless, gossip that Anne and her ministers favoured the succession of her half-brother rather than the Hanoverians continued, despite Anne's denials in public and in private.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne was unable to walk between January and July 1713.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] At Christmas, she was feverish, and lay unconscious for hours, leading to rumours of her impending death.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She recovered, but was seriously ill again in March 1714.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Despite failing health, which her doctors blamed on the emotional strain of matters of state, she attended two late-night cabinet meetings that failed to determine Harley's successor.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] A third meeting was cancelled when she became too ill to attend.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She was rendered unable to speak by a stroke on 30 July 1714, the anniversary of Gloucester's death, and on the advice of the Privy Council handed the treasurer's staff of office to Whig grandee Charles Talbot, 1st Duke of Shrewsbury.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne died around 7:30 am on 1 August 1714, aged 49.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Electress Sophia of Hanover had died on 28 May, two months before Anne, so Sophia's son, George, Elector of Hanover, succeeded pursuant to the Act of Settlement 1701.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The possible Catholic claimants, including Anne's half-brother, James Francis Edward Stuart, were ignored.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Elector's accession was relatively stable: a Jacobite rising in 1715 failed.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Marlborough was reinstated, and the Tory ministers were replaced by Whigs.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Duchess of Marlborough "unduly disparaged" Anne in her memoirs, and her prejudiced recollections persuaded many early biographers that Anne was "a weak, irresolute woman beset by bedchamber quarrels and deciding high policy on the basis of personalities".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Historians have since viewed Anne more favourably.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In his biography of 1980, Edward Gregg presents the Queen as a woman of invincible stubbornness, who was the central figure of her age.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In the opinion of modern historians, traditional assessments of Anne as fat, constantly pregnant, under the influence of favourites, and lacking political astuteness or interest may derive from sexist prejudices against women.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Author David Green noted, "Hers was not, as used to be supposed, petticoat government.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] She attended more cabinet meetings than any of her predecessors or successors, and presided over an age of artistic, literary, scientific, economic and political advancement that was made possible by the stability and prosperity of her reign.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In architecture, Sir John Vanbrugh constructed Blenheim Palace and Castle Howard.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Queen Anne-style architecture and Queen Anne-style furniture were named after her.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Writers such as Daniel Defoe, Alexander Pope, and Jonathan Swift flourished.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Henry Wise laid out new gardens at Blenheim, Kensington, Windsor and St James's.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The union of England and Scotland, which Anne had fervently supported, created Europe's largest free trade area.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The political and diplomatic achievements of Anne's governments, and the absence of constitutional conflict between monarch and parliament during her reign, indicate that she chose ministers and exercised her prerogatives wisely.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In 1702, Anne adopted the motto *semper eadem* ("always the same"), the same motto used by Queen Elizabeth I.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The Acts of Union declared that: "the Ensigns Armorial of the said United Kingdom be such as Her Majesty shall appoint".
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In 1707, the union was heraldically expressed by the impalement, or placing side by side in the same quarter, of the arms of England and Scotland, which had previously been in different quarters.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] The new arms were: Quarterly; I and IV, Gules three lions passant guardant in pale Or (for England) impaling Or a lion rampant within a double tressure flory-counter-flory Gules (for Scotland); II, Azure, three fleurs-de-lis Or (for France); III, Azure, a harp Or stringed Argent (for Ireland).
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] In Scotland, a separate form of arms was used on seals until the Act of Union.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] Anne had seventeen pregnancies, of which five were live births.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/anne-queen-of-great-britain] None of her children survived to adulthood.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] The **Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies**, also called the **Scottish Darien Company**, was an overseas trading company created by an act of the Parliament of Scotland in 1695.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] The act granted the company a monopoly of Scottish trade to India, Africa and the Americas, extraordinary sovereign rights and 21 years of exemptions from taxation.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] Financial and political troubles plagued its early years.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] The court of directors was divided between those residing and meeting in Edinburgh and those in London, amongst whom were both Scots and English.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] They were also divided by business intentions; some intended to trade in India and on the African coast, as an effective competitor to the English East India Company, while others were drawn to William Paterson's Darien scheme, which ultimately prevailed.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] In July 1698 the company launched its first expedition, led by Paterson, who hoped to establish a colony in Darien (on the Isthmus of Panama), which could then be used as a trading point between Europe and the Far East.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] Though five ships and 1,200 Scottish colonists landed successfully in Darien, the settlement was poorly provisioned and eventually abandoned.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] A second, larger expedition (launched before the fate of the first was known) took up the deserted settlement, but was quickly besieged by the Spanish.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] More than a thousand succumbed to hunger and disease, and in April 1700, two ships carried the few survivors home.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] In 1700–01 the Company sent further expeditions to Java and China, but suffered shipwrecks at Malacca and seizure of cargo by pirates at Madagascar.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] The company was involved in the Indian Ocean slave trade between 1698 and 1708.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] On 26 June 1695 the Parliament of Scotland passed the **Company of Scotland Act 1695** (c.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] 10), *Act for a Company Tradeing to Affrica and the Indies*, establishing the Company of Scotland trading to Africa and the Indies.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] The subscription book of the Company of Scotland was opened in Edinburgh on 26 February 1696, inviting investments from a minimum of £100 up to a maximum of £3,000.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] Such was the popularity of the scheme that on the first day alone 69 subscriptions were taken, worth £50,400.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] A second book was open in Glasgow between 5 March and 22 April.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] Although attempts to raise funds in London, Hamburg and Amsterdam had been blocked, by the beginning of August 1696 the full target of £400,000 sterling had been reached.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] When the Company of Scotland was first formed, it was managed by its promoters, whose key task was to encourage subscriptions to the company.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] Once the subscription target of £400,000 sterling had been reached, however, the company required a more formal management structure.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] On 3 April 1696 a general meeting of subscribers elected a committee of twenty from their number to work with the promoters to establish rules and a constitution.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] By the middle of the month they had agreed that the company would be managed by a court of directors and a council general.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] The court of directors was to be an elected body with a maximum of fifty members, with each £1,000 of stock entitling its holder to one vote in the election.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] Twenty-five members would be elected by the subscribers, with up to a further twenty-five being elected by the first twenty-five.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] Subscribers with a holding of £1,000 or more could stand for election.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] A different director was to act as president of the court at each meeting.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] The first court of twenty-five directors was elected by shareholders on 12 May 1696.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] Candidates for election had to own at least £1,000 of company stock and so a limited number of shareholders, 119 out of a total of 1,320 (1,267 individuals and 53 institutions), were eligible to become directors.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] The court's directors came from across Scotland's wealthy classes, comprising two nobles, eight merchants and 15 lairds.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] Shortly afterwards, the first twenty-five directors appointed William Paterson and three others as additional directors.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] From July 1696 the court of directors met in the company's offices in Mylne Square on Edinburgh's High Street.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] The council general was to be a larger body than the court of directors, comprising both the directors themselves and representatives of the remaining subscribers, with one representative for each £10,000 of stock.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] Whilst the court of directors was responsible for the day-to-day running of the company, the council general was convened to discuss major decisions, such as capital-raising, the election of future directors and the payment of dividends.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] The council general was only convened as and when there were matters to discuss, and therefore meetings were not held at regular intervals.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] All told, the venture, dubbed the Darien Scheme, drained Scotland of an estimated quarter of its liquid assets and played a key role in leading the country to the Act of Union 1707 which united the kingdoms of Scotland and England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] The new joint government, in a political bargain, agreed to cover the costs of winding up the Company of Scotland, in addition to compensate for servicing the English national debt and higher taxes for Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/company-of-scotland] All were Scots by birth except John Smith, who was Lord of the Treasury for the English parliament.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] The Convention of the Estates of Scotland a sister-institution to Parliament of Scotland, comprising the three estates of bishops, barons and representatives of the Scots burghs.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] Historically, it had been summoned by the king of Scots for the limited purpose of raising taxes, and could not pass other legislation.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] Unlike the English Convention Parliament of 1689, the 1689 Scottish Convention was also a contest for control of the Church of Scotland or Kirk.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] Scotland played no part in the landing and Dutch invasion by "force of arms" by Prince William of Orange and his wife Mary (daughter of James II) in England and there was little enthusiasm for William and Mary, by November 1688 only a tiny minority actively supported James.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] Many of William of Orange's exile advisors were Scots, including Melville, Argyll, his personal chaplain, William Carstares, and Gilbert Burnet, his chief propagandist.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] News of James's flight led to celebrations and anti-Catholic riots in Edinburgh and Glasgow and on 7 January 1689, the Scottish Privy Council asked William to take over, pending a Constitutional Convention to agree a settlement.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] In February, an English Convention appointed William of Orange and his wife Mary as joint monarchs of England.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] As James had not been present in the kingdom when he fled to France.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] The Scots had to proceed on a Scots Constitutional basis.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] In Scotland elections were held in March 1689 for a Scottish Convention; 'Conventions of the Estates of Scotland' were identical to Parliaments of Scotland in composition but only discussed specific issues, the previous one held in 1678 to approve taxes.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] Of the 125 delegates elected, 75 were classed as Presbyterian, 50 as Episcopalian, making the Convention a contest over control of the Church of Scotland, as well as the limits of royal authority.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] William's nominee, the 3rd Duke of Hamilton, was elected President of the Constitutional Convention, although his son remained loyal to James.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] Despite being a minority, the Episcopalians were hopeful of retaining control of the Kirk since William supported the retention of bishops.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] However, on 12 March, James landed in Ireland and on 16th, a Letter to the Convention was read out, demanding obedience and threatening punishment for non-compliance.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] Public anger at this meant some Episcopalians stopped attending the Convention, claiming to fear for their safety while others changed sides.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] Tensions were high, with the Duke of Gordon holding Edinburgh Castle for James and Viscount Dundee recruiting Highland levies.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] This exaggerated the Presbyterian majority in the Convention which met behind closed doors guarded by its own troops.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] The English Parliament held James 'abandoned' his throne by fleeing from London to France; since the same argument could not be used in Scotland, the Convention argued he (Scots) "FOREFAULTED" (forfeited) it by his actions, listed in the Scots Articles of Grievances and "CLAIM of RIGHT" Act 1689.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] The Scots throne was offered to Mary and William, who was granted regal power on the basis he held the throne *de facto*, by right of conquest.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] In an attempt to preserve Episcopalianism, the Scottish bishops proposed Union with England but this was rejected by the English Parliament.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] On 11 April, the Convention ended James' reign and adopted the Articles of Grievances and Claim of Right Act, making Parliament the primary legislative power in Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] On 11 May 1689, William and Mary accepted the Scottish throne and the Convention became a full Parliament on 5 June.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] The 1689 Jacobite Rising highlighted the new regimes' reliance on Presbyterian support and led to the final expulsion of bishops from the Kirk in the 1690 Act of Settlement.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] The ending of Episcopacy isolated a significant part of the Scottish political class; in the 18th century, Nonjuring Episcopalians were a key support base of the Scottish Jacobite movement.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland-1689] James and the Jacobites viewed the Convention as "illegal" and argued that the declaration of forfeiture was not valid because the authority of a Scottish Convention of Estates was limited to revenue raising measures and the Convention had not been called by the rightful king.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland] The **Convention of Estates of Scotland** was a sister institution to the Scottish Parliament which sat from the early sixteenth century.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland] Initially, it was only attended by the clergy and nobles, but the burgh commissioners were later added.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland] The Convention of Estates differed from Parliament in that it could be summoned by the King for the limited purpose of raising taxation, but could not pass other legislation.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland] Like its predecessor General Council it played an important role in political and legislative affairs in Scotland in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland] During the Glorious Revolution in Scotland, the Scottish Privy Council asked the King of England, William of Orange, to summon the Convention of Estates of 1689 to determine the throne of Scotland.
[src:adam-cockburn-lord-ormiston/convention-of-estates-of-scotland] It offered it to William and Mary, adopting the Articles of Grievances and Claim of Right Act 1689, and transformed itself into a full parliament.
